I then found out that the xxxProxy file had not been generated in the client project for some reason.
Kathy, back to you as discussed. Need to determine why the proxy hasn't been generated. Feels like an caught/suppressed exception may be the cause.

I ran into this problem when selfhosting with the target driver I200603090213  after fixing bug 131154.  Note that this problem only happens intermittently.  I got it in one workspace and not the other.

The reason the proxy file is not generated is because we need to figure out the name of the proxy file that should be generated by walking the WSDL model of the generated WSDL file.

The WSDL file is like the following:

<wsdl:service name="ConverterService">
 <wsdl:port name="Converter" binding="impl:ConverterSoapBinding">
     <wsdlsoap:address location="http://localhost:8080/t5/services/Converter"/>
 </wsdl:port>
</wsdl:service>

With the workspace that has problem, the extensibility element of the port returns as:

eclipse.wst.wsdl.internal.impl.UnknownExtensibilityElementImpl

In the workspace that does not have the problem, the extensibility element of the port returns as:

eclipse.wst.wsdl.binding.soap.internal.impl.SOAPAddressImpl

I debug this problem with Kihup and we suspect this to be something to do with different orders of plugins getting loaded for the different workspace.

We found that the IExtension class is defined in 2 plugins depended by the org.eclipse.wst.wsdl plugin:

org.eclipse.core.runtime.compatibility.registry 
org.eclipse.equinox.registry

The method org.eclipse.core.runtime.IExtension.getDeclaringPluginDescriptor() 
is only defined in the org.eclipse.core.runtime.compatibility.registry plugin but not the org.eclipse.equinox.registry plugin.

Since depending on which plugin get loaded first, the problem might or might not happen.  

We also noticed that the dependency on org.apache.xerces plugin was added recently to org.eclipse.wst.wsdl, it might have changed the plugin dependency is some way causing this problem to show up.

Kihup, I'll send you the 2 workspaces to reproduce the problem (they are too big to include as attachments).

BTW ... while I'm sure the base would like "compatibility" to work wonderfully, 
I believe IExtension.getDeclaringPluginDescriptor is quite deprecated so moving to non-deprecated code will probably help too.
